Parallel tests
By default all unit test assemblies should run in parallel mode, which is the default. Unit tests
shouldn't depend on any shared state, and so should generally be runnable in parallel. If the tests
fail in parallel, the first thing to do is to figure out why; do not just disable parallel tests!
For functional tests it is reasonable to disable parallel tests.
var ex = Assert.Throws<InvalidOperationException>(
() => fruitBasket.GetBananaById(1234));
Assert.Equal(
"1234",
ex.Message);
Assert.Equal(true, someBool);
Assert.True("abc123" == someString);
Assert.True(list1.Length == list2.Length);
for (int i = 0; i < list1.Length; i++) {
Assert.True(
String.Equals
list1[i],
list2[i],
StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase));
}
Assert.True(someBool);
Assert.Equal("abc123", someString);
// built-in collection assertions!
Assert.Equal(list1, list2, StringComparer.OrdinalIgnoreCase);

